00:04:43,120 --> 00:04:45,450
For the Cell reference column, let's start

88
00:04:45,450 --> 00:04:48,430
by selecting the left hand side of the two capacity

89
00:04:48,430 --> 00:04:49,860
constraints.

90
00:04:49,860 --> 00:04:52,780
The Operator should be less than or equals,

91
00:04:52,780 --> 00:04:54,510
and the Value should be the right hand

92
00:04:54,510 --> 00:04:58,130
side of these two capacity constraints.

93
00:04:58,130 --> 00:05:00,840
Now, let's make the demand constraints.

94
00:05:00,840 --> 00:05:04,880
In Cell reference, just directly select the six decision

95
00:05:04,880 --> 00:05:06,610
variables.

96
00:05:06,610 --> 00:05:09,350
Make sure the Operator is less than or equals,

97
00:05:09,350 --> 00:05:13,480
and for the Value, select the six demand constraints.

98
00:05:13,480 --> 00:05:15,662
This was a bit easier than what we did before,

99
00:05:15,662 --> 00:05:17,120
because we didn't have to type them

100
00:05:17,120 --> 00:05:19,420
all out in our spreadsheet.

101
00:05:19,420 --> 00:05:21,060
Now, let's do a similar thing for

102
00:05:21,060 --> 00:05:24,260
the non-negativity constraints, where in Cell reference,

103
00:05:24,260 --> 00:05:26,690
we select the six decisions.

104
00:05:26,690 --> 00:05:30,230
The Operator this time should be greater than or equals,

105
00:05:30,230 --> 00:05:33,370
and for the Value, just type zero.

106
00:05:33,370 --> 00:05:37,630
Make sure in Options that the Linear Solver is selected,

107
00:05:37,630 --> 00:05:40,800
